{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657487/1924022501/0324.xml":{"full_text":"-MOTORIZING AKRON\nIS PROIGFAILURE\nTiremakers Are Now Ready\nto Compromise\u2014Firestone\nDrops His Campaign.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nXKW YORK, February 23\u2014\" The\nnickel or nothing\" provision under which\nbuses are expected to operate in\nAkron, Ohio, has not proved attrac\ntive to the big bus companies, ac\ncording to automobile and street\ntransportation men throughout the\ncountry. Akron has been without\nMreet car service since February 1,\nwhen Mayor D. C. Rybolt notified the\nNorthern Ohio Traction and Light\nCompany that its franchise would not\nj he renewed except on a 5-cent fare\nand free transfer basis.\nHarvey s, Firestone, tire manufac\nturer and one of the supporters of\nthe plan to \"put Akron on rubber\ntires.\" lias abandoned active partici\npation in llte plan to rubberize the\n\u2022hty and is preparing to go to Florida.\n\u20191 lie Northern Ohio Company has of\nto operate for sixty days on a\n--cent fare, with 1 cent additional for\nTransfer, until its books and accounts\n<ould be investigated and its claim\nthat it Is impossible to operate\nwithout loss on a 5-cent fare can be\nsubstantiated. Mr. Firestone, after\nconferring with the traction company\nofficials, has announced that he con\nsidered the company\u2019s proposal a fair\n\u2022lie and thought it should be accepted.\nHe also indicated he would not finance\nany bus companies.\n2**o Fords Disposed of.\nAt the time street \u2019car service\nceased. Mr. Firestone was quoted in\nthe Akron Beacon-Journal as say\ning; \u201cI feel that it is my duty and\nthe duty of every citizen to give the\ncity officials every assistance pos\nsible to motorize the city. This can\nand will be done.\u201d At that lime Mr.\nFirestone considered from the Ford\nCompany 200 cars. These were sent\nby the manufacturer from Ohio deal\ners, who dispatched them with bills\nof lading attached. Firestone re\nturned 120 ->f these and since that\nrime has disposed of the remaining\neighty to the Akron Transportation\nCompany.\nOther tire manufacturers have\nceased to urge the complete motori\nzation of Akron on the ground that\nthe time is not ripe for such a de\nvelopment. They point out that in\nmany cities street railways .are also\nrunning bus service in conjunction\nwith their lines, instead of in cotn\npetition, and that such service lias\nbeen satisfactory and tending toward\nthe increased consumption of bus\ntires. Financial Interests identified\nwith public utilities in a number of\nlarge centers arc also alleged to be\nopposed to the continuation of the\nsituation in Akron. These are among\nihe factors which have influenced\nUrge bus companies not to establish\na unified service in that city.\nJohn S. Ritchie, formerly head of\nthe Fifth Avenue Coach Company In\nNew York and now identified with\nlarge bus manufacturing interests in\nTiicago who was called in by Mayor\nKybolt, said frankly that a 5-cent\nbus fare was impossible.\nOpponent Akron Methods.\nWilliam O\u2019Neil, president of the\nGeneral Tire and Rubber Company,\nwho has advocated acceptance of\nsome temporary agreement with the\ntraction company, said; \"1 have never\ni pposed buses. g do a large busi\nness with bus lines- over the country,\nand their use is essential, but I taink\nit is a dire' mistake to attempt to\nmotorize a city the size of Akron m\nthe wav the attempt is being made.\nJf the bus is right as a common car\nrier it will come info its -own in the\nplain course of economic evolution.\n\u201cWe have talked fare and rates\nfirst, when service should have been\nthe first consideration. Akron doesn t\nwant busses to fall or their use to be\nretarded throughout the country, tor\nit would reflect on the tire business.\nThe plan lias failed so far. v ut tl is\nnot the failure of the busses.\n115 People In One Bos.\nThe city council of Akron has\nt turned down the proposal of tem\nrotary operation by the t-action com\nran y and Mayor Uybvrt declares that\nbus service will be improved and\nthat the citv administration will i\nmaintain Its position until the peo\nple signify that they believe that\nposition wrong.\nThere are now al>iut 100 busses and\n173 jitneys in operation and the city\nouncil has granted franchises to\ntwo bus concerns to operate on lini\nited routes at a 5-cent fare, with\ntt-cent transfers. Those favoring a\ncompromise say that in some cases\n115 people have been loaded into\nbusses seating thirty-six and that\nr-s there is no unified service, it costs\nsome citizens from 20 cents to to\ncents to get to their places of busi\nness.\nIn the meantime, business men in\nAkron are still hoping that the way\nhas not been closed finally for some\nsolution of the problem which will\nallow operation of both street cars\nand busses.\nSOUTHERN WILL INSTALL\nSIGNALS AND TELEPHONES\nbpccial Dispatch to The Star.\nATLANTA, Ga., February 23. \u2014To\nincrease the capacity of its Atlanta-\nBlrmingham line to provide for grow\ning traffic, the Southern railway will\ninstall the automatic electric block\nsignal system and also construct two i\ntelephone circuits, so as to substitute\ntho telephone for the telegraph for\ntrain dispatching.\nThe signal system will consist of\n202 masts, carrying signals of the new\ncolor-light type, located at intervals\nof 1 miles.\nTODAY\u2019S COTTON PRICES.\nWeek Opens With Irregular Trend\nin Price Moves.\nNEW YORK, February 25. \u2014Conflict-\ning influences were indirectly at work\ni in the cotton market during today\u2019s\nI early trading. The opening was steady\nat a decline of five points to an ad\nvance of sixteen points. March was\nunder considerable pressure of liquida\ntion in preparation for possible notices\ntomorrow and this had an unsettling\neffect on Hie general list, although\n\u2022some of the March sellers were re\nbuying in later months, and there was\nconsiderable buying of new crop posi\ntion on reports of unfavorable wither\nin the south.\nNEW ORLEANS. February 23.\nThe cotton market opened with a. good\nupward trend, due to higher Liverpool\ncables than due and spot sales there of\n14,000 bales, of which 12,800 were\nAmerican. First trades showed gains\nof seventeen to twenty-five points, com\npared with the previous close. New\nYork, not improving as much as the\nlocal market, prices eased off slightly\nafter the opening, but soon rallied on\nreports of snow In west Texas and a\nstorm warning for the Texas coast.\nNEW YORK, February 23.\u2014Cotton\nfutures, 11;45 a.m., bids steady. March,\n29.65; May, 30.01; July, 28.42; October,\n26.60; December, 26.12.\nNEW ORLEANS, February 25.\nCotton futures, noon bids, steady.\nMarch, 29.90; May, 29.42; July, 28.75;\nOctober, 25.77; December, 25.40.\nV. S. TREASURY CERTIFICATES\n(Quotations furnished by Redmond Co.)\nt Noon.\nBid. Offer.\n4\u00bb4s March 13. 1024 100\n\u20224%b March 15. 1024 J()0\n\u2022Is June 16, 1924 UK* MO 8-32\nsi<ia June 16, 1921 HNHa 100 5 s\no\u2019-jH September 15, 1924.. 100 23-82 100 29-32\n4 -Is Ik-.-cmlK-r 15. 1924... MO 332 MO 9-32\n\u2022l March 15, 1923 MO 17 32 MO 21-32\n4Lb June 15, 1925 100 9-32 300 13-32\nWss December 15, 1928... 100% 100%\n4\u00bbi* March 15, 1928 100 25-32 100 29-32\n4 >40 September 13. 1928.. 90 13-19 100 1-16\n4%b March 15. 1027 Ml 1-18 Ml .1-18\nAlls DecujwtMC Mi1. .4 mim 100%\nFINANCIAL.\nNEW YORK CURB MARKET\nReceived by Private Wire Direct to The Star Office\nBV WILLIAM F. IIKFKJBHNAX.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, February 25.\u2014Lower\nprices were the rule on tho curb\nmarket today, but a few Industrial\nfavorites continued strong despite\nthe general downward tendency. The\nbuying in Kresge Department Stores,\nwhich resulted in an advance of over S\npoints last week, kept on. the stock\ngetting to a new top around 51%.\nReports are to the effect that an an\nnouncement of the taking over of\nanother department, store by this\ncompany will be made soon.\nSilica Gel voting trust firsts also ro\nj slated the selling and reached their best\nI prices above 28. Operations for the\nj rise in American Light, and Traction\n(appeared to have been abandoned.\nThere was nothing new in the oil\nsituation at Washington to account for\nthe selling In the oil group. The sharp\nadvance at the close last week natural\nNEW YORK, February 25. \u2014Follow-\ning is an official list of bonds and stocks\ntraded in on the New Y\u2019ork Curb Mar\nket today;\nsue ill RONDS.\ntlu.iisan.ls. High. Low. 2:15.\n2 Alum 7s 1925 102% IC*2% 102*4\n2 Alum 7s new \u201933... 10*i' 3 106% 106%\n6Am das Elec 6k.. 94% 94 94\nM Am Light 6\u00bb w w. Ml'* fiOl lot\nlAm Sumatra To 7'-js 97*, 97*\u00ab 97\\\nlAm Rolling Mills As 99% 99*4 1*9%\n2Am Thread Co 65... 101% 101 Kit\u2019,\nH Anaconda As 102 Ml*. 101 *J\n5 Anglo Am Oil 7'->h, 102 M 2 M 2\n30 At fit AWIS S 3\u00bb 53 5214 58\n5 Reavertwiard 8s 77 77 77\n1 Iteth Steel 7s \u201935... 102\u2019, 102 T 4 M2\u2019,\nt Can Nat tty Equip 7\u00bb 107\u20194 107\u2019, 107\u00bb\u00bb\n1 Charcoal Co Am Ba. 93 '4 93% 03%\nChi Northw 5, wi 9244 92*4 92 >4\nhi. It IA. rae 5%\u00bb 98*4 \u00bb8 a 98*4\n5 Chi Baton Sta IS 0\u00ab. 98 98 98\n6 fit Scrv 7* C 93% 931* 9314\n1 fit Serv \u201ds I) 90 90 90\nS Con, Gas KalM tie A M3*4 103*4 108%\n1 Cnl\u00aban Tel 7%s 107 107 I'T\n5 I tee re A Co 7%s lot Vi MU, 4 101*4\n5 Itetr-dt Citv Gag t\u2019w. 101 *4 lot Ml',\n7 Dunlop Tr Vt Hub 7\u00ab 93'i 98% 98'-\nt fisher Iloily Os '28.. 99'a 99% 99\u2019,\n1 Galena Signal Oil 7s. I<4>, I**4% I(4**\n4 Genera! Pet 0s 181'* 96% 96%\n1 Grand Trunk 6%k.. 105'- 10514 MT,%\n5 Gulf Oil of Pa 55... 95\"* 93 a* 95\n1 Hoed Rubber 7, JOU4 Ml 14 10114\n1 lilt Matc h OKs w 1.. 93% 93-V 934*\n5 Kennecott Cop 7*.... M4'* 104% 104'*\nI L tv l.tg real ost 7s 103% M3*h 103%\n4 Manitoba Pow 75.... 97 90% 90%\n5 Market St Hy 7s 991* 99*4 99**\n33 MSIP Uy 5%, wl 87% 87% 87%\n3 Morris A Co 7%s 100 Mo MO\