 Ift 1A\n10 Wear Utah 31 .31 .31\n20 White Caps 04 .04 .04\n5 Yukon Gold .70 .70 .70\njWALL STREET WORRIED\nBY TAX PLAN TALK\nCorporation Reports for 1923 Also\nProve Disappointing in\nMany Instances.\ni\ni Special Dispatch to The Star.\nXE\\V YORK, February 25.\u2014Today's\n1 irregular decline on the stock t-x\n--j change was to he set down partly to\nj outside and partly to inside causes.\nThere was nothing at tho oil inquiry\nIn AVashington to disturb sentiment,\nbut AVall street, which up to a week\nago had been counting with confi\ndence upon the Mellon tax program,\nwas naturally depressed by the for\nmidable opposition which has de\nveloped.\nHope Is still felt that the Senate\nwill act very differently from the\nHouse and that a bill will be worked\nout in conference which will be' rea\nsonably satisfactory to business men\nand will be approved by the Prcsl\nj dent. This is something, however,\nwhich will not be setled for two or\nthree months to come.\nWhat perhaps had more immediate\ninfluence upon the market of the day\nwere a number of 1923 corporation\nreports, some of them showing what\nwas expected, others distinctly dis\nappointing, but in both Instances not\ncalculated to promote speculative en\nthusiasm. The one thing that was\nconstantly said, even from the be\nginning of 1923, was that it was to be\na good year so far as gross business\nwas concerned, but a year of stiff\ncompetition and small profit margins\nfor many companies.\nThe truth of this statement Is now\nbeing demonstrated.\nBefore Yon Invest\u2014lnvestigate.\nIt's queer how careful a man can\nbe after he's lost his money. Abe\nMartin says that a man who is not\nsatisfied wtih 6 per cent and his\nmoney are soon parted.\nTOBACCO PLANS OUT.\nProducts Export Corporation In\nterested in Mexico.\nXEW YORK, February 25.\u2014The\nTobacco Products Export Corporation\nhas been named as one of the in\nterests Involved in the plan to invest\n$25,000,000 In Mexico to develop to\nbacco and other Industries. Tho\ncompanies. It Is said, would take\npart In negotiations looking to a\ntobacco monopoly, _ but, was not afflli\nated with interests which recently\nacquired cigarette factories in\nMexico.\nThe largest iron mine in the United\nStates Is near nibbing, Minn,\nWOULD HALT SALES\nOF ENERGY STOCK\nCourt Has Lightning Bolt\nClaims Investigated and\nAction Follows.\nBy the Assofiatcil Pro**.\nNEW YORK, February 25.\u2014An\norder directing the TomaJelll Elec\ntronic Corporation to show cause in\nthe supreme court on February 2T\nwhy It should not be restrained from\nselling any more of its stock to the\npublic, has been obtained by Attorney\nGeneral Sherman from Justice Wag\nner, It is announced here. The order\nwas handed down after an investiga\ntion by Deputy Attorney General\nWilbur Chambers, who was assisted\nby the Hotter Easiness Hureuu of\nNew York.\nApproximately 20,000 shares of\nthe stock already havo been sold for\nSI,OOO, the investigators said. The\nprincipal owner, Juan J. TomadelU,\nwho, according to a company pros\npectus, has Invented a process for\ndrawing dynamic energy from the air.\nThe prospectus asserts that the in\nvention already has created a light\nning holt off\u00ab, 000,000 volts, and\nthat eventually It will supplant elec\ntric lights.\nDr. Cyprlen Maillaux, past presi\ndent of the American Institute of\nElectrical Engineering, and Dr. Clay\nton 11. Sharp, past president of the\nIlluminating Engineering Society, re\ntained to Investigate the claims of\nTomadelU, reported that nothing\nshown to them indicated that tin- ap\nparatus had a possibility of practical\napplication or commercial value.\nTho corporation factory is at Har\nrison. X. J. Thirteen thousand shares\niof the stock were underwritten by\nWilliam D. Aekerson of Jersey City,\nwho, Mr. Chambers declared, luler\nwithdrew when the company took\nover the sale of Its stock, voting to\nTomadelU ai! of the $1,090.000 par\nvalue voting slock and SIOO,OOO non\nvoting stock.\nCOMMODITY NEWS\nWIRED STAR FROM\nENTIRE COUNTRY\nNORFOLK, Va.. February 25.\u2014The\nnew Ford Motor Company plant to\nbe built here this spring will cost\nmore than $2,000,000. Ford cars and\ntractors will he distributed through\nneighboring slates, exported, and\nsent coastwise from this point.\nCLEVELAND. February 25.\u2014The F\nH. Stearns Company has just closed a\ncontract with a Montreal company to\nhandle from 500 to 1.000 Stearns cars\nIn the Hritlsh empire this year, start\ning March 1. and to take a minimum\nof 1,000 and a maximum of 2,000 cars\nannually for the next nine years.\nKAN FRANCISCO. February 25.\nDevelopment of the iiHiige crop has\nbeen retarded by \u00bbne dry winter and\nestimates for It- 1921 production\nhave been upset. The crop now ts ex\npected to fall 1,800 car loads below\nthe amount expected.\nFORT WORTH. February 25\u2014Ad\nvancing prices fur hides are affording\nTexas stock men a market at a\nprofit. In the last ten weeks prices\non steer hides have increased 5 to 10\ncents a pound, and calf skins c-veu\nmore.\nATLANTA, February 25.\u2014Southern\ncotton mill men arc looking toward\nSouth America as a market for their\nwares, according to one large manu\nfacturer here. He said southern mills\nalready had establlsiied fine connec\ntions in Argentina, which opened a\nfine field for yams, hosiery and\ntowels.\nCAPE CIIARLEK, Va., February 25.\n\u2014Prospects are that the famous\nEastern Shore white potato wllj he\nplanted on an acreage 10 per cent\ngreater than last year, instead of 10\nP\u00bbr cent less, as urged by authorities.\nTho farmers began planting this\nweek. Tho normal yield is 3,000,000\nbarrels.\nBROTHERHOOD\u2019S BANK\nASSETS ARE DOUBLED\nNEW YORK. February 25.\u20141 n the\n(two months that have elapsed since\njits formation, the Brotherhood of\nLocomotive Engineers\u2019 Co-operative\nTrust Company has doubled both Its\nassets and the number of its custo\nmers. according to a report on the in\nstitution\u2019s progress Issued by its\npresident. Warren K. Stone.\n\u201cIn three years\u2019 time the Brother\nhood system of banking,\u201d says Mr.\nStone\u2019s statement, referring to the re\nsults obtained in this and other cities,\n\"has proved that the co-operative plan\nis not a dream. The actual profits\ndistributed to Its savings depositors\nbrought in a return on their accounts\nof 5 per cent for the year ended De\ncember 31, 1923, after dividends to\nthe stockholders, making tho proper\nprovision for surplus.\u201d\nWILL SPEND $5,000,000.\nGeorgia Railway to Eliminate\nForty-Three Grade Crossings.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nATLANTA. February 23.-\u2014Tho Cen\ntral of Georgia railway will award\ncontracts April 1 for $5,000,000 worth\nof track improvements between Co\nlumbus, Ga., and Birmingham, Ala.\nIncluded In the work if. elimination\nof forty-three crossings and the.\nstraightening of eighty-threc curves.\nBuild An Income With Our\n6%%\nFirst Mortgage Notes\nMANY of our clients put aside SIOO every\ntime their savings amount to that much,\nand their interest starts immediately. The\nreal way to build a fortune or income is to in\nvest as fast as you save.\nOur First Mortgage Notes, are in denomina\ntions of SIOO and upward.\nAnd they have endured fifty-four years of\nnational and international change and upheaval\nwithout loss to an investor.\nSwartzell, Rheem Hensey Co.\n727 15th Street N.W.\n54 Years Without Loss to an Investor\nB. 0. PRESIDENT FINDS\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK GOOD\nWillard Reports on Tour Through\nWest\u2014Railroad Traffic\nImproving.\nSpecial Dmpatrh P* The Star.\nBALTIMORE, February 25.\u2014Daniel\nWillard, president of tho Baltimore\nand -Ohio railroad, just back from a\ntour of the west, is more convinced\nthan ever that there is no country in\nthe world that can be compared with\nthe United States. Regarding the\nbusiness situation, he said:\n\u201cI got the distinct impression at\ni ll points that the people generally\nwere feeling very much encouraged\nconcerning the business outlook for\nthis year. I was told that there had\nbeen a perceptible improvement lu\nthe business since the first of Jan\nuary.\n\"I spent a day in Chicago conferring\nwith our representatives and others\nin position to know something about\nthe business outlook, and every\nwhere J found a feeling of distinct\nhopefulness, not to say optimism,\nconcerning the present year.\n\"While the business of the Balti\nmore and Ohio Company during the\nfirst two weeks in January was sub\nstantially lower In volume than the\namount handled during the same\nperiod a year ago, I am happy to say\nthat at the present time the passen\nger business is running somewhat\nahead of a year ago, and the freight\nbusiness fully as good. I feel dis\ntinctly hopeful concerning the out\nlook for tlie present year.\u201d\nCANADIAN BUTTER HAS\nGROWING U. S. MARKETS\nEDMONTON, Alta. February 25.\nGovernment grading of butter and\ncream is developing Alberta into one\nof the principal dairying provinces of\nCanada, according to the annual re\nport for 1923 of O. I\u2019. Marker, pro\nvincial dairy commissioner.\n\"Creamery butter graded by the\ngovernment service in 1923.'\u2019 said Mr,\nMarker, \u201ctotaled 10,764.762 pounds.\nThis was an increase of more than\n3.060,0**9 pounds over the 1922 grad\ning. of this total 21.6 per cent was\ngraded special, and 64,7 per cent\nfirsts. Mr. Marker placed the value\nof the 1923 dairy output at $22,975,000.\nButter from Alberta, he paid, is be\ning exported to Great Britain and\neasjern United Stales, where it has\nestablished a firm market. Because\nof the strictness of the government\ngrading, lie pointed out. it lias built\nup an international reputation for ex\ncellency.\n\u201cNEVER\u201d\n1 \u2014a loss of as much as a sing'.e\nj penny in either principal or\ninterest to a client is a record\nwe prize most highly.\n1 The careful and conservative\nI methods that have establlsiied\nI for ns tills enviablt record in\nthe past will undoubtedly\nguide us in tho future.\nI Notes of $250 up Bearing\nn\nNow On Hand\nChas. D. Sager\ni 924 Fourteenth Street N.W.\nI :\u00abs\nLoan Dept, Main ]\\l\nEQUITABLE\nCo-Operative Building\nAssociation\nOrganised 1870\n4ifk TEAR COMPLETED\nAaaetn s4,7sS,t*oj<2\nSurplus 31.545.3U0.nl\nAccomplishes Most\nHyftcin\u00abttc MTliif is tbe tm#i\neft-cti\u00bbe (dvibb \u00abf \u2022rcumalatlnt\nmnDty. Joint the Equitlble and sir\u00ab\nWilli be\u00abt ren'llt*.\nSubscription for the\n86th Issue, of Stock\nBeing Received\nShares, $2.50 Per Month\nEQUITABLE BUILDING\n915 F St N.W.\nJOHN JUV ED 8 ON. Freetlrg*\nFRANK P. UKESIDE. Scfy.\nWe Buy and Sell\nLiberty Bonds\nTreasury Notes\nEtc.\nBond Department\nThe Washington Loan\nand Trust Company\n900 F Street\n620 17th Street\nCOTTON EXPORTS UP\nABOUT 75,000 BALES\nValue of Manufactures Less Than\nYear Ago, Commerce Depart\nment Reports.\nHaw cotton exports from the L'nitfd\nStates totaled 546,833 bales in Janu\nary, an Increase of approximately\n\"3,000 bales over January a year ago,\nthe Department of Commerce an\nnounced today. The value of the raw\ncotton exported In January was given\nat {34,683,356, as compared with $63,-\n256,426 for January. 1923.\nDuring last month the exports of\ncotton manufactures were valued at\n$9,354,789, while the value of cot\nton manufactures exported in Janu\nary, 1928, was $10,499,999.\nDEMAND PAY INCREASE.\n6.525 Building Men Take Action on\nWages in St. Louis.\nlUnpstch to The MUr.\nST. LOUIS. February 25. \u2014Union\nmen In the building trades here to\nthe number of 6,323 are demanding\nincreases in wages. Many non-union\nnegro bricklayers and plasterers are\narriving here, and from 10 to 15 per\ncent of the work now in progress\nIs being done by them.\nProminent Real Estate Firm\nWants\nA Young Man\nBetween 20 and 30\nYears Old\n\u2014to specialize in the sale S\nof first trust (mortgage)\nnotes.\nMust be well educated and S\nof good appearance\u2014excel-\n5 l